The paper deals with fundamental data structures for string processing, specifically suffix arrays and LCP arrays. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes algorithms for constructing these data structures in optimal time and space, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. The paper also mentions that these data structures are widely used in information retrieval (IR), which suggests that it may belong to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category. The paper also deals with strings of distinct characters, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes algorithms that are optimal in time and space, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, as optimization is a key aspect of many machine learning algorithms.
